ladders.explanation:
The brute force approach solves the longest common substring problem by exhaustively comparing every possible substring of the first string against every possible substring of the second string. The intuition is straightforward: if we check all possibilities, we're guaranteed to find the longest match. This works because substrings are contiguous sequences, so we can systematically generate them using start and end indices. The algorithm uses three nested loops: the outer two loops generate all substrings of str1 (by varying start and end indices), and the innermost loop compares each str1 substring against all possible substrings of str2. For each comparison, we check character-by-character equality until a mismatch occurs or we reach the end of the shorter substring. We track the maximum length found and optionally the substring itself. The time complexity is O(n³) because we have O(n²) substrings from str1, O(n²) from str2, and O(n) for comparison in the worst case. Space complexity is O(1) as we only store a few variables. This connects directly to the key subroutine (L1) which is the substring comparison logic. Common mistakes include: 1) Not resetting comparison indices properly, 2) Off-by-one errors in substring bounds, 3) Inefficient re-computation of substrings, 4) Forgetting to handle empty strings. The real pattern involves careful loop boundary management and early termination when mismatches occur.

Pseudocode:
function longestCommonSubstring(str1, str2):
    max_len = 0
    result = ""

    for i from 0 to len(str1)-1:
        for j from i to len(str1)-1:
            substr1 = str1[i:j+1]

            for k from 0 to len(str2)-1:
                for l from k to len(str2)-1:
                    if (j-i) == (l-k):  # Same length check
                        match = True
                        for m from 0 to (j-i):
                            if str1[i+m] != str2[k+m]:
                                match = False
                                break
                        if match and (j-i+1) > max_len:
                            max_len = j-i+1
                            result = substr1

    return result

This sub-routine is the heart of the brute force approach. Given a fixed substring from the first string, we need to check if it appears anywhere in the second string. The intuition is that we slide the substring along every possible starting position in the second string and compare character-by-character. This works because if the substring exists in the second string, there must be some starting index where all characters match consecutively. We iterate through all possible starting positions in str2 (from 0 to len(str2)-len(substr)), and at each position, compare the substring character-by-character with the corresponding segment of str2. If all characters match, we've found an occurrence. The time complexity is O(m*n) where m is the length of the substring and n is the length of str2, since we have n starting positions and up to m comparisons each. Space complexity is O(1). This feeds into L0 by being called for each substring of str1. Common mistakes include: 1) Not checking bounds properly (trying to access beyond str2 length), 2) Continuing comparison after finding a mismatch, 3) Not handling empty substrings correctly. The pattern involves careful index arithmetic and early termination.

Pseudocode:
function substringExists(substr, str2):
    substr_len = len(substr)
    str2_len = len(str2)

    if substr_len == 0:
        return True

    for i from 0 to str2_len - substr_len:
        match = True
        for j from 0 to substr_len-1:
            if substr[j] != str2[i+j]:
                match = False
                break
        if match:
            return True

    return False

This core logic generates all possible substrings of a given string, which is fundamental to the brute force approach. The intuition is that any substring can be uniquely identified by its starting index and ending index. By varying these two indices across all valid ranges, we can enumerate every substring. This works because substrings are defined by contiguous characters, so we need all pairs (i,j) where i ≤ j. The algorithm uses two nested loops: the outer loop controls the starting index (i from 0 to n-1), and the inner loop controls the ending index (j from i to n-1). For each pair (i,j), we extract the substring str[i:j+1]. This generates substrings in order of increasing starting position, then increasing length for each starting position. Time complexity is O(n²) since there are n(n+1)/2 substrings, each taking O(1) to extract if we just track indices. Space complexity is O(1) if we only store indices, or O(n) if we store all substrings. This feeds into L1 by providing the substrings to check. Common mistakes include: 1) Using j < i instead of j ≥ i, 2) Off-by-one errors in slice indices, 3) Generating non-contiguous sequences, 4) Missing single-character substrings. The pattern is clean double-looping with proper bounds.

Pseudocode:
function getAllSubstrings(s):
    n = len(s)
    substrings = []

    for i from 0 to n-1:
        for j from i to n-1:
            substr = s[i:j+1]
            substrings.append(substr)

    return substrings

This building block extracts a substring from a string given starting and ending indices. The intuition is that strings are sequences of characters accessible by index, and a substring is just a contiguous slice of these characters. This works because strings support indexing, and we can iterate from the start index to the end index (inclusive) to collect characters. The algorithm takes the original string, start index i, and end index j (where i ≤ j). It creates a new string by concatenating characters from index i through j. In many languages, this is a built-in operation (like s[i:j+1] in Python), but understanding the manual process is important. We initialize an empty result string, then loop from i to j, appending each character to the result. Time complexity is O(k) where k = j-i+1 (the length of the substring). Space complexity is O(k) for the new string. This feeds into L2 as the operation performed for each (i,j) pair. Common mistakes include: 1) Using exclusive instead of inclusive end index, 2) Not validating that indices are within bounds, 3) Confusing 0-based and 1-based indexing, 4) Not handling empty substrings (when i > j). The pattern involves careful index arithmetic and bounds checking.

Pseudocode:
function extractSubstring(s, i, j):
    if i < 0 or j >= len(s) or i > j:
        return ""  # Invalid indices

    result = ""
    for index from i to j:
        result = result + s[index]

    return result

This basic operation compares two strings to determine if they are exactly equal. The intuition is simple: two strings are equal if they have the same length and every character at each position matches. This works because strings are ordered sequences, so we can compare them position-by-position. The algorithm first checks if the lengths are equal—if not, they can't be equal. Then it iterates through each index from 0 to length-1, comparing characters at the same position. If any pair differs, the strings are not equal. If all pairs match, the strings are equal. Time complexity is O(n) where n is the length of the strings (we traverse once). Space complexity is O(1) as we only use a few variables. This feeds into L3 as part of substring comparison. Common mistakes include: 1) Not checking length first, 2) Using assignment (=) instead of comparison (==), 3) Comparing beyond the shorter string's length, 4) Not handling empty strings correctly. The pattern is straightforward iteration with early exit on mismatch.

Pseudocode:
function stringsEqual(s1, s2):
    if len(s1) != len(s2):
        return False

    for i from 0 to len(s1)-1:
        if s1[i] != s2[i]:
            return False

    return True
